From Wickapedia:
The Beretta 950 Jetfire is a simple blowback pistol with a single action trigger mechanism and tip-up barrel. The frame is made out of aluminium alloy, the slide and barrel are carbon steel.
Early models (*950B* Pre-1968) do not have a safety lever, employing a half-cock notch on the hammer instead. Later models (*950BS* Post-1968) are provided with an external safety lever.
[edit]Intended market

The Beretta 950 Jetfire is a backup, self-defense pistol that is intended for undercover agents, police officers or individuals licensed to carry a concealed firearm for self-defense.[citation needed]
[edit]Limitations

The .25 ACP cartridge is not very powerful, but a well placed shot is lethal. The safety system is very basic. The accuracy of the pistol is adequate although the small grip and short sight radius may limit some shooters to be effective only at short ranges. Its small grip also makes it prone to bite (the slide can cut the top of the shooters hand when fired). As the pistol lacks a shell extractor, relying instead on blowback pressure to clear the shells, misfires are easily removed manually by tipping up the barrel and prying out. The pistol is also produced in .22 short model.
[edit]Technical data



Beretta Jetfire with the tip-up barrel open
Type: Beretta 950 Jetfire
Trigger system: Single-action only
Caliber: .25 ACP
Capacity: 8 rounds magazine, 9 rounds if first chambered
Frame material: Aluminium light alloy
Slide and barrel material: Carbon steel
Grip material: Plastic
Barrel length: 60 mm

Height: 87 mm
Width: 23 mm
Mass: 280 g
Safeties: none (950B) or left-side thumb switch (950BS)
Magazine release: Lower left grip heel pushbutton.
Production years: 1952–2003.
Production locations: Beretta Italy (pre 1968), Beretta do Brasil (late 1960s - early 1970s), Beretta USA, (1970s to date)

title: For Sale:  Chiappa Rhino 200DS
postcontent:
Chiappa Rhino 200DS (2" barrel). If you don't know about this gun, do some research then come back and buy mine. 

This is THE CHOICE for a daily carry revolver. The cylinders are flattened for a thin profile. Also, it fires from the BOTTOM cylinder butting the bore in line with your hand. Full power 357 magnum loads feel like a hot 38 spl load. It's a 6 shot, DA/SA concealed carry monster. The front sight on mine has a floruscent green painted ramp to help with your sight picture pick up. 

Mine is a little bit of an ugly baby which is why the price is lower than what you'll typically find. The previous owner had it duracoated green. There is some holster wear on the duracoat and it has the cylinder ring that all revolvers get once they've been cycled a few times. 

Comes with factory box, papers, service record, holster and some ammo if we're meeting face to face. If you have property and you are close I will let you test fire it, bring a standard 357 mag with you to compare, the 200DS will win every time. 

Can ship to your FFL for a small fee if you are to far away to meet face to face.

title: For Sale:  Egyptian Maddi AK Cerakoted And ATI polymer stock
postcontent: Egyptian Maddi Ak 47. Made in 1995 and it has been Cerakoted Coyote tan and a gray ATI folding stock set added. I had heard some bad stuff about Maddi and when I got this rifle I did some research on them and found out that the rifle is as close of copy to a true Russian Ak as there is. The reason for that is that in the 60s when the Israelis’ kicked the Egyptians butts once again the Russians picked up a complete AK factory and moved it to Egypt and ran it for them for years. There are some later ones that had some problem but the ones made up into the late 90s are good. This one does not appear to have been shot much. The ATI stock set is a recoil reducing set with rails and is a very nice addition to the AK. Comes with 2 metal 30rd magazines.
